@Caraline Neil 
3. I think that somewhat shows how the communities around me value their freedom of speech. In my immediate era, there are high-income and strongly right-leaning communities that are actively changing laws in the surrounding areas and important buildings such as schools. A highly debated example of this currently happening is the "Don't Say Gay" bill that is sweeping through the schools. The older, richer, and right-leaning communities that make up most of the voting pool in my state are voting for these laws that restrict freedom of speech while they preach for it at the same time. If you were to interview younger more left-leaning communities such as the UCF surrounding area you may find the opposite, people who don't prioritize freedom of speech but actively protest against laws such as the "Don't Say Gay" bill.
4. The ratio of those who prioritize freedom of speech in their personal politics.

@Ashley 
I agree with your statement of people being affected by this because they may not be using their freedom of speech due to fear or backlash. 

The title can accurately capture what is going on in this graph.

@Nathan C and @Jack What a wonderful idea! Some variability would be natural in different samples, especially if we introduce another variable such as the region of the country. You may be curious about how region plays in and how your survey compares to the Northeast Region as well as the entire country. You can check out tinyurl.com/FOS-NYT to see the statistics for 26 subgroups of the sample of individuals who were contacted for this national poll. The question for this graph is #22, and although this graph did not include this subgroup, the poll did. 

When you get done with your surveys, come back to this post and let us know. I would be very interested as well.
And @Nathan C, I appreciate your desire for more acceptance and forgiveness. Keep aiming for it! I am not sure of the solution, but if more of us keep trying, we have a better chance of improving.
